{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626190"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:34:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:34:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17059"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17059"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.61,0.06,0.03,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9749"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62893"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProbenecid is a medication that affects the transport of various substances in the kidneys. It is commonly used in the treatment of gout and to alter the excretion of certain medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of probenecid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases glomerular filtration rate","Blocks organic anion transporters in proximal tubules","Blocks potassium channels in collecting ducts","Activates aquaporin water channels","Inhibits sodium-glucose cotransporters"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EProbenecid works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking organic anion transporters in proximal tubules\u003C/strong\u003E of the kidney. This reduces the secretion of various organic acids, including many drugs, leading to increased plasma concentrations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases glomerular filtration rate\u003C/strong\u003E - Probenecid has no direct effect on glomerular filtration and works primarily through tubular mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks potassium channels in collecting ducts\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is characteristic of potassium-sparing diuretics such as amiloride, not probenecid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates aquaporin water channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Aquaporin channels are regulated by antidiuretic hormone and are not affected by probenecid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits sodium-glucose cotransporters\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of action for sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitors used in diabetes treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistorically, probenecid was used to prolong the half-life of penicillin by reducing its renal excretion. Today, it is mainly used to treat gout and to prevent drug interactions by affecting the renal handling of various medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Probenecid inhibits organic anion transporters in the proximal renal tubules, reducing the excretion of many drugs.","Probenecid was historically used to prolong penicillin half-life by reducing its renal excretion.","Probenecid increases blood levels of drugs like methotrexate and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs by reducing their renal clearance."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17059"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:16:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T21:18:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9749"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77386"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (i